I have very little to say in defense of the Star Wars child, but statements like this have always bothered me.<br>
A couple resources regarding the case of Stella Liebeck vs the McDonald's Corporation: <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stella_Liebeck_v._McDonald's_Corporation">Wikipedia entry</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->, <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.atlanet.org/ConsumerMediaResources/Tier3/press_room/FACTS/frivolous/McdonaldsCoffeecase.aspx">American Trial Lawyers' Association fact-sheet</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->.<br>
The following is largely paraphrased from these sources.<br>
Stella Liebeck initially sought $20,000 to pay for medical costs that resulted from the accident.  These costs covered an 8-day hospital stay, during which she underwent skin grafting to treat third-degree burns that she received on 6 percent of her body, including (quoting ATLA) &quot;her inner thighs, perineum, buttocks, and genital and groin  areas.&quot; McDonalds refused to pay the $20k, so she took them to court over it.<br>
What came out during the trial (in particular, during discovery) was interesting.  Between 1982 and 1992, over 700 claims had been filed against McDonalds over injuries received as a result of coffee burns; a number of them were third-degree burns.  McDonalds required its franchises to maintain a temperature of 180-190 degrees F in their coffee.  140 degrees is about average for other establishments; an expert witness testified that at 180 degrees, liquid &quot;will cause a full thickness burn to human skin in two to second seconds&quot;, but that as the temperature approaches 150 degrees, the burn risk decreases exponentially.  A McDonalds QA manager testified that they were aware of the burn risk (not just to the skin, but to the mouth and throat, simply from drinking the coffee), and had no intention of cooling their coffee.<br>
The jury awarded Liebeck $200k, plus $2.7 million in punitive damages; the court reduced this to $160k and $480k punitive.  It is unclear how much she actually received, since following the trial McDonalds settled with her privately.<br>
One point of punitive damages is to prevent companies from playing the sort of statistics game that Edward Norton plays for his employer in <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Fight Club</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> -- intentionally putting people at risk with the intention of paying off a certain number of small claims per year.  McDonalds was well aware of the risk, as their own people testified; the judge referred to their conduct as &quot;reckless, callous, and willful.&quot;<br>
There are a lot of bogus torts that get filed, and some of them pay off, which is indeed distressing.  But I'm not sure this woman, however, is the example that you're looking for. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub40.ezboard.com/bthesaryrntavern.showUserPublicProfile?gid=fixli>Fixli</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle><span style='color:pink;'>Tavern Floor Sweeper</span></span><br>  Posts: 15<br> <font color=#6FB8DD>(7/25/03 10:47 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub40.ezboard.com/fthesaryrntavernthefurnace.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3421.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: The People vs Stella Liebeck</span><hr size=1> Also note from the Wikipedia entry, McDonald's basically admitted guilt by offering to pay the initial $800. The argument really then became over about how much they should have to pay, not whether McDonald's was responsible.<br>
